      <hedline>
        <hl1>Of Two Minds on Social Security</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Katz letter, commenting on June 19 article on Vice Pres Al Gore proposal for special retirement accounts, says Social Security is better bargain for taxpayers (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Vice President Al Gore's Social Security proposal is preferable to Gov. George W. Bush's proposal because the Gore plan would not divert needed payroll-tax revenue from the Social Security Trust Fund (front page, June 19).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Vice President Al Gore's Social Security proposal is preferable to Gov. George W. Bush's proposal because the Gore plan would not divert needed payroll-tax revenue from the Social Security Trust Fund (front page, June 19).</p>
        <p>Actually, Social Security is a better bargain for taxpayers than any kind of individual retirement account because of its dramatically lower administration costs.</p>
        <p>Indeed, why is either presidential candidate proposing to subsidize investment bankers' I.R.A. fees before Social Security is fully financed through the baby-boom generation's lifespan?</p>
        <p>Far better to put the same money into the Social Security Trust Fund itself, and then allow that fund's administrators to seek higher returns by investing a prudent portion of its portfolio in the stock market.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL KATZ  Berkeley, Calif., June 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
